S107.shortDescription: Methods should not have too many parameters
S107.fullDescription: A long parameter list can indicate that a new structure should be created to wrap the numerous parameters or that the function is doing too many things.

S112.shortDescription: General exceptions should never be thrown
S112.fullDescription: Throwing such general exceptions as Exception, SystemException, ApplicationException, IndexOutOfRangeException, NullReferenceException, OutOfMemoryException and ExecutionEngineException prevents calling methods from handling true, system-generated exceptions differently than application-generated errors.

S1125.shortDescription: Boolean literals should not be redundant
S1125.fullDescription: Redundant Boolean literals should be removed from expressions to improve readability.

S1135.fullDescription: TODO tags are commonly used to mark places where some more code is required, but which the developer wants to implement later.

S3776.shortDescription: Cognitive Complexity of methods should not be too high
S3776.fullDescription: Cognitive Complexity is a measure of how hard the control flow of a method is to understand. Methods with high Cognitive Complexity will be difficult to maintain.
